    <item>
      <title>Satellite Observation of Aerosol-Precipitation Relationship</title>
      <link>https://cxfan-kamisama.github.io/cxfan_starfan/main/zh/project/acp_gpm_modis/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 30 Jun 2019 00:00:00 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://cxfan-kamisama.github.io/cxfan_starfan/main/zh/project/acp_gpm_modis/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;abstract&#34;&gt;Abstract&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The adjustment of cloud amount to aerosol effects occurs to a large extent in response to the
aerosol effect on precipitation. This is studied here for marine boundary layer water clouds by
analyzing the dependence of rain intensity, as measured by the radar onboard the Global
Precipitation Measurement (GPM), on cloud properties as measured by MODIS. Here we show that
detectable rain initiates when the drop effective radius at the cloud top exceeds 14 $\mu$m, and
precipitation is strongly suppressed with increasing cloud drop concentration ($N_d$), which
contributes to the strong dependence of cloud amount on aerosols. This dependence of
precipitation on $N_d$ and cloud geometric thickness presents a simple framework for precipitation
susceptibility to aerosols, which explains other kinds of previously observed relationships. Our
results further show that sorting data by cloud geometrical thickness and using alternative CCN
proxy rather than aerosol optical depth (AOD) are critical for studying aerosol-cloud-precipitation
interactions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1 id=&#34;keywords&#34;&gt;Keywords&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Aerosol, Cloud, Precipitation, Climate, GPM, MODIS&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
